Normalizing a vector means adjusting its components so that it has a length (or magnitude) of 1, while preserving its direction. This is often useful in various applications, such as machine learning algorithms, computer graphics, and physics simulations. Here’s how you can normalize a vector in several common programming languages:

### Python (using NumPy)
```python
import numpy as np

# Example vector
vector = np.array([3, 4])

# Normalize the vector
normalized_vector = vector / np.linalg.norm(vector)

print("Original vector:", vector)
print("Normalized vector:", normalized_vector)
```

### Python (using math library)
```python
import math

# Example vector
vector = [3, 4]

# Calculate the magnitude
magnitude = math.sqrt(vector[0]**2 + vector[1]**2)

# Normalize the vector
normalized_vector = [vector[0] / magnitude, vector[1] / magnitude]

print("Original vector:", vector)
print("Normalized vector:", normalized_vector)
```

### C++ (using Standard Template Library)
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <cmath>

// Function to normalize a vector
std::vector<double> normalize(const std::vector<double>& vec) {
    std::vector<double> normalized_vec;
    double norm = 0.0;

    for (size_t i = 0; i < vec.size(); ++i) {
        double COMPONENT = vec[i];
        norm += COMPONENT * COMPONENT;

        // Prevent division by zero
        if (norm!= 0) {
            normalized_vec[i] = COMPONENT / norm;
        } else {
            normalized_vec[i] = 0; // Handle the case of a zero vector
        }
    }

    return normalized_vec;
}

int main() {
    std::vector<double> original_vector = {3.0, 4.0};
    std::vector<double> normalized_vector = normalize(original_vector);

    for (double val : normalized_vector) {
        std::cout << val << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}
```

